Fig. 3
). The female was carrying two eggs and observed at approximately 1500 hrs while positioned face down on a shaded surface outside a deep crevice into which she attempted to retreat prior to capture. The male was captured later that night at 2200 hrs while abroad in essentially the same area. These observations suggest this species in nocturnal.
